Multi-disciplinary: neuroscience, statistics, data analysis</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58b6f2dc8bcad7.11352036-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>Data analysis, exchange of ideas, paper writing.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>Data analysis design, exchange of ideas, paper editing.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>University of Liege</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>Belgium, Kingdom of</gtr:country><gtr:description>Liege</gtr:description><gtr:id>F40F5328-AB57-459B-A128-291B412ED5AD</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Schartner, M.M., Seth, A.K., Noirhomme, Q., Boly, M., Bruno, M.A., Laureys, S., &amp;amp; Barrett, A.B. (2015). Complexity of multi-dimensional spontaneous EEG decreases during propofol induced general anaesthesia. PLoS ONE 10(8): e0133532.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>5448fd43c14a16.61637488-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>Contribution of data</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>Analysis of data</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2013-01-01</gtr:start></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Blog article for PRIME Economics</gtr:description><gtr:form>Engagement focused website, blog or social media channel</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>2D49EF7C-5C14-47DB-825E-056EC7EF3077</gtr:id><gtr:impact>I contributed a blog post for Policy Research in Macroeconomics (PRIME), which is a network of macroeconomists, political economists and professionals from related disciplines who seek to engage with a diverse audience in order to de-mystify economic theories, policies and ideas. The goal was to alert the public to the potential for complexity science type thinking to solve problems in macroeconomics. The title of the article is &amp;quot;Macroeconomics: there's hope&amp;quot;</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58b6f966769558.60474379</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.primeeconomics.org/articles/macroeconomics-theres-hope</gtr:url><gtr:year>2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>One research package has demonstrated how certain measures of signal diversity can robustly index various states of consciousness. Consistent robust decreases in signal diversity were observed in electrophysiological data from general anaesthesia and deep sleep compared to wakeful rest, while increases were observed in data from participants administered with psychedelic substances. The latter observations constituted the first time that increases in signal diversity have been seen for any state, relative to wakeful rest. One of the measures, synchrony coalition entropy, is completely new: it computes the variability over time of the constitution of the set of channels that are in synchrony. Together the findings further our understanding of the relationship between consciousness and neural dynamical complexity. There are two published papers from this research, in PLoS ONE and Neuroscience of Consciousness, and a third paper is currently under review.

I have published a paper in Frontiers in Psychology that lays out a new approach for the Integrated Information Theory of Consciousness (IIT) that will make it more compatible with realistic fundamental physics. IIT is currently the most promising theory for describing fundamentally how matter can give rise to subjective experience. Its elegant core idea is that consciousness derives from intrinsic information, i.e. that which is independent of the frame of reference imposed by outside observers. The problem with previous formulations of IIT is that, by being formulated only for networks of abstract discrete elements, they are not applicable to standard models of fundamental physical entities. In modern physics, fields are considered the most fundamental entities. Thus, in my paper I posit that consciousness fundamentally arises from information intrinsic to the electromagnetic field generated by the brain, and I describe how IIT should be reformulated to provide a measure of the intrinsic information in a continuous field configuration.

I have published a paper in Physical Review E that will help open up a whole new approach to characterizing and quantifying information sharing amongst complex system variables. Shannon information theory has provided extremely successful methodology for understanding and quantifying information transfer in systems conceptualized as receiver/transmitter, or stimulus/response. However, in its current form it does not provide a complete description of the informational relationships between variables in a system composed of three or more variables. Specifically it can't specify the redundant or synergistic information provided by two potential `source' variables about a potential `target' variable. Redundant information is that which is common to both sources, while synergistic information is that which only arises from knowing both sources. There have been a few recent studies that have begun addressing this with respect to systems of discrete variables. My study is the first that addresses this for continuous random variables. I have obtained formulae for redundancy and synergy that are valid for a broad class of systems composed of normally distributed random variables. These quantities are non-trivial in that redundancy is independent of correlation between sources, and synergy can either increase or decrease with correlation between sources. My formulae will find application to a broad spectrum of continuous time-series data, and in particular to neurophysiological data such as EEG.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Academic sector impact: I received invitations to present my work on measuring synergistic and redundant information at two international workshops attended by leading players on the neuroscience and computer science fronts of complexity science.

Clinical sector impact: My work on measuring conscious level could impact on the clinical assessment of consciousness in traumatic brain injury patients and during general anaesthesia. My collaboration with leading neurologists at research hospitals in Milan and Liege will ensure the taking up of any opportunity for incorporating my scientific findings into this realm. My measures have recently been applied to data from participants administered with psychedelic drugs in a world-leading laboratory at Imperial College London. The group there are trialling the use of psychedelic drugs to treat anxiety and depression, and the complexity measures developed in my research could prove useful in monitoring physiological changes in patients during trial treatments. I will present my work at the next meeting of the South of England Neurosciences Association, a forum for exchange between clinicians and clinical neuroscientists.

Public impact: My mentor, Anil Seth regularly mentions my work at public talks. Through public speaking and the publishing of a lay-person's account of my work I hope to further stimulate the public's intellect with my unique stance on consciousness. There is a history of research at Sussex influencing local artists, and thus I hope my work will inspire some artwork.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>8798D3E0-2754-4104-B97E-2E4CBC935226</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5463924d695663.43358481</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Creative Economy,Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Users/abb22/</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>8CF1D959-982C-4EDF-94D7-5FC956AFEC7E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Increased spontaneous MEG signal diversity for psychoactive doses of ketamine, LSD and psilocybin.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Scientific reports</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/0043307a11eb43c101a2e3408441bee0"><gtr:id>0043307a11eb43c101a2e3408441bee0</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Schartner MM</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2017-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>2045-2322</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>5a8454a7702696.69206675</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>329D57BF-0BB5-4232-88D8-924A0048C755</gtr:id><gtr:title>Solved problems and remaining challenges for Granger causality analysis in neuroscience: A response to Stokes and Purdon (2017)</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>ArXiv e-prints</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/2f14ed907d6f2e5249181ba52c71d437"><gtr:id>2f14ed907d6f2e5249181ba52c